The Pocket of Summer

There was a time when happiness fit in your pocket.

It weighed almost nothing.

Maybe it was a smooth rock you found for no reason. A crumpled Pokémon card. A lucky marble. Twenty dollars from your grandmother folded twice. The key to your bike lock. A receipt from the arcade that you refused to throw away because somehow it proved the day had happened.

Back then, the world felt larger than the map. Empty parking lots became kingdoms. A walk to the mailbox became an expedition. The ice cream truck was a national holiday.

You don’t actually miss being a kid.

You miss believing that ordinary Tuesday afternoons still had the potential to become stories.

So here’s a trade.

Keep your mortgage. Keep your responsibilities. Keep your calendar and your coffee and your unread emails.

But leave one pocket empty.

Not for your phone.

For something wonderfully unnecessary.

A seashell from a trip.
A tiny dinosaur.
A polished coin.
A LEGO astronaut.
A note someone wrote you.
A ridiculous keychain that makes exactly one person smile—you.

Not because you’re trying to go backward.

Because you’re reminding yourself that life is allowed to contain small treasures.

Adults deserve pocket-sized wonder too.

The world never stopped hiding little miracles.

We just stopped checking our pockets.